{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505472","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505472"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:31:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:31:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2445"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2445","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2445"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.02,0.02,0.28,0.45]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2445"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113351"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2445","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2445"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2445"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95372"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"1046"},{"type":"tags","id":"1747"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1969"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1987"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41716"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113351","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113351"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 57-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-week history of recurrent epistaxis and easy bruising. He reports increasing fatigue over the past three months. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He works as an accountant and does not drink alcohol to excess or use other substances.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears pale but well. His pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 135/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 15/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. There is no lymphadenopathy or hepatosplenomegaly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHaemoglobin: 100 g/L (130-180)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EWhite cell count: 2.8 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (3.6-11.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPlatelets: 28 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (140-400)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ELactate dehydrogenase: 700 U/L (240-480)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EFibrinogen: 0.9 g/L (1.50-4.50)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EProthrombin time: 25 seconds (11-13.5)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EActivated partial thromboplastin time: 49 seconds (25-35)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ED-dimer: 25 mg/L FEU (\u003C0.5)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPeripheral blood film shows many blasts and atypical promyelocytes, which are intermediate in size, with open chromatin, multiple prominent nucleoli, bilobed and folded nuclei, lightly basophilic cytoplasm with many coarse azurophilic granules. Some promyelocytes contain many Auer rods.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important immediate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Imatinib","Dasatinib","Ruxolitinib","Rituximab","All-trans retinoic acid"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAcute promyelocytic leukaemia is a medical emergency that often presents with pancytopenia and disseminated intravascular coagulation. Laboratory clues include prolonged clotting times, hypofibrinogenaemia, and markedly elevated D-dimer, alongside a peripheral blood film demonstrating abnormal promyelocytes with multiple Auer rods. The major early cause of death is haemorrhage due to coagulopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAll-trans retinoic acid\u003C/strong\u003E should be commenced immediately when acute promyelocytic leukaemia is suspected, prior to genetic confirmation of the PML::RARA fusion. It induces differentiation of promyelocytes and rapidly improves the coagulopathy, reducing early haemorrhagic mortality. Early initiation alongside supportive care (cryoprecipitate to maintain fibrinogen, platelets, and careful avoidance of invasive procedures) has transformed outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImatinib\u003C/strong\u003E is a tyrosine kinase inhibitor that targets BCR-ABL and is used in chronic myeloid leukaemia and Philadelphia chromosome-positive acute lymphoblastic leukaemia; it has no role in acute promyelocytic leukaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDasatinib\u003C/strong\u003E also targets BCR-ABL and is used in chronic myeloid leukaemia and Philadelphia chromosome-positive leukaemias; it is not effective in acute promyelocytic leukaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERuxolitinib\u003C/strong\u003E is a Janus kinase inhibitor used in myelofibrosis and polycythaemia vera and is not indicated for acute promyelocytic leukaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERituximab\u003C/strong\u003E is an anti-CD20 monoclonal antibody used in B-cell lymphomas and some autoimmune diseases; acute promyelocytic leukaemia is a myeloid malignancy and does not express CD20.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAcute promyelocytic leukaemia requires prompt recognition and treatment with all-trans retinoic acid-based regimens (often with arsenic trioxide), which achieve cure rates exceeding 90% when instituted early.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Acute promyelocytic leukaemia often presents with pancytopenia and disseminated intravascular coagulation, including low fibrinogen and markedly elevated D-dimer.","All-trans retinoic acid should be started immediately when acute promyelocytic leukaemia is suspected to rapidly reverse coagulopathy and reduce haemorrhage risk."],"references":["Ryan MM. Acute Promyelocytic Leukemia: A Summary. J Adv Pract Oncol. 2018 Mar;9(2):178-187.","Yilmaz M, Kantarjian H, Ravandi F. Acute promyelocytic leukemia current treatment algorithms. Blood Cancer J. 2021 Jun 30;11(6):1-9."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95372"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2445"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95372"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-11T17:43:14+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-11T17:44:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2445"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113351"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"73","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/73"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Post-graduate","synonyms":null,"description":"Not suitable for a medical student","position":2,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1046","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1046"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Epistaxis","synonyms":["Nasal hemorrhage","Nosebleeds","Nose bleed"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-06-10T00:04:35+09: